40|$|We study {{computational}} {{problems for}} two popular parliamentary voting procedures: the <b>amendment</b> <b>procedure</b> and the successive procedure. While finding successful manipulations or agenda controls is tractable for both procedures, our real-world experimental {{results indicate that}} most elections cannot be manipulated by a few voters and agenda control is typically impossible. If the voter preferences are incomplete, then finding possible winners is NP-hard for both procedures. Whereas finding necessary winners is coNP-hard for the <b>amendment</b> <b>procedure,</b> it is polynomial-time solvable for the successive one...|$|R
